<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 3:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If1d9adb16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I9f85f1c0933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>3.</label.designator><headtext>Powers of the Panel</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94cd28b5e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>3:5.</label.designator><headtext>Constitutionality of statute</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The constitutionality of the statute[<footnote.reference refid="If1d9fbd06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] creating the Panel and defining its powers has rarely been challenged in the courts. <eos/><bos/>Because of the minimal opportunity for review, there are few appellate court decisions regarding the actions of the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If1da22e06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel has ruled on the constitutionality of the statute in one case. <eos/><bos/>In that case defendants raised the argument that the broad transfer power of the statute, authorizing transfer for coordinated or consolidated pretrial proceedings in a district where a defendant did not have requisite minimum contacts for exercise of personal jurisdiction, violated the Due Process Clause of the Fifth Amendment. <eos/><bos/>The Panel&apos;s discussion of this contention was terse: <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“We have considered this constitutional argument and find it without merit.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="If1da49f06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>] Parties have not generally thereafter relied on constitutional arguments before the Panel.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If1d9adb16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If1d9fbd06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304913953" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I50366fc06b3e11e9bfe8894985907fa8">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The statute is reprinted in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:19" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If1d9fbd16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 3:19</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If1da22e06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Review of Panel decisions, and of’ transferee and transferor courts is discussed in Chapter 11.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If1da49f06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304913953" w-serial-number="1975107365" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1400" ID="I5037a8416b3e11e9bfe8894985907fa8">In re Sugar Industry Antitrust Litigation, 399 F. Supp. 1397, 1400 (J.P.M.L. 1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 3:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
